HEADWORD: Evanesce
<hw>Ev`a*nesce"</hw> <pr>(⟦ecr⟧v`⟦adot⟧*n⟦ecr⟧s")</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Evanesced</conjf>
<pr>(⟦ecr⟧v`⟦adot⟧*n⟦ecr⟧st")</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Evanescing</conjf>.
<pr>(⟦ecr⟧v`⟦adot⟧*n⟦ecr⟧s"s⟦icr⟧ng)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L.
<ets>evanescere</ets>; <ets>e</ets> out + <ets>vanescere</ets> to
vanish, fr. <ets>vanus</ets> empty, vain. See <er>Vain</er>, and cf.
<er>Evanish</er>.]</ety> <def>To vanish away; to become dissipated and
disappear, like vapor.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I believe him to have <qex>evanesced</qex> or evaporated.</q>
<rj><qau>De Quincey.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Evanescence</ent>⟦br⟧
